This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already very widespread, but provides details that the fossils can usually not provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
The scientists say that the plumage of this animal was brown chestnut on the top and pale or carotenoid on the bottom.
This discovery also allows us to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that the feathers of dinosaurs do not have a fully developed shaft, which is called the rachis, but nevertheless show other characteristics typical of feathers – barbs and barbules – the researchers have deduced that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used in flight but rather for the regulation or display of temperature. The researchers have suggested that, even if it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows an adult plumage and not the down of a chick.
Scientists clarify that it is indeed the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals a plumage belonging to an adult individual, and not to a young one.
